title: For Trade:  Russian Saiga AK, unconverted
location: N. Columbus/ Harris County, Columbus, GA, Georgia
postcontent:
I'm considering trading my nearly-new, unconverted Saiga Ak47 variant, for cash and a clean, all-matching SKS.
  If you're looking at this ad, I assume you know the deal on the Saigas, but for general info, the Saigas are made in Russia, in the same factory as their military AK47, but come in a "sporterized" configuration to conform to import regulations. Once imported, they are often converted to legally accept regular, hi-capacity AK magazines of all types. Doing this is not expensive or very complicated.
  These are widely acknoweldged as being among the highest quality AK variants around, and are buit using brand-new,chrome lined barrels, no used,surplus parts whatsoever.
Also, last year the "Administration" banned any future imports of Russian made weapons, adversely affecting price and availabiltiy of these rifles. It is unlikely in the extreme that this ban is ever rescinded, so once they're gone......they're gone.
  I think I've fired the rifle only one time with some freinds a couple years ago, and we may have shot 4 whole boxes through it, surely no more than a hundred rounds. It is dead-nuts accurate, and flawlessly reliable.
I have at least 4 of the factory 10-round magazines for it (I may even have 5 total). 
  I had another Saiga that I converted a while back, but sold it, and kept this one unconverted intentionally, being that it's 10-rd capacity would hopefully keep it under the radar from any future hi-cap bans,which I think will be a possible benifit of rifles like these (and SKS's).
  These are curently selling in the $600+ range, if you can find any in-stock at all. SKS prices on the other hand, have been falling like a stone, with very clean Chinese versions running consistently at about $350 on the local used market ( and that's before even counter-offering), so you do the math. 
  As usual, prospective traders must be legal to own firearms, be a Georgia resident over age 18, and have valid ID to prove it (of course, I'll show my DL and carry permit,as well.)
The photo is one I just snatched off the interwebz, but my rifle is identical, you seen one, you seen 'em all.
I will also sell the rifle outright, but since I'm after an SKS, I thought I might do better shooting for a trade+cash.
Thanks for looking.......

postcontent:
Armalite recently revamped their product lineup so you won't be able to find details of this model on their website any more.  They do still offer a similar AR-10(T) rifle, with the main differences being the rifle is an A-series with a 20" barrel.  I did manage to save the specs though before it disappeared from their site:
	• 7.62 NATO & .308
	• 7075-T6 Forged Flattop Receiver with Picatinny Rail and Forward Assist
	• 16" Stainless Steel Match Barrel with an advertised 1 MOA accuracy
		○ Triple Lapped 
		○ RH 1:10" Twist
		○ 4 Groove
	• A2 Flash Hider
	• Aluminum round free-float handguard
	• Picatinny Gas Block (.398" lower than receiver rail)
	• Forged Lower Receiver
	• A2 stock

I did not buy the rifle as a whole unit - I bought the complete upper receiver directly from Armalite last year but picked up the lower receiver used a few years ago.  I'm not sure what kind of life the lower receiver went through before I had it but it's performed flawlessly for me since I've had it (it does have a scuff at the bottom of the magazine well though).  The upper receiver has less than 500 rounds through it and is in perfect shape except for the tool marks that I so bone headedly inflicted on the barrel upon switching back to the factory flash hider from my muzzle brake.  The charging handle has been upgraded with a Badger Ordnance lever but the original lever is included in case it's not to your liking.

If you're not familiar with the Armalite AR-10s, they have two different series - this one is their B-series takes only Armalite steel magazines while their A-series will accept either their old waffle magazines or 308 PMAGs.  The receivers between the two series are NOT interchangeable.

I'm asking $1550, including two 20 round magazines and the Plano hard case Armalite ships their rifles in.  Cash offers only, please.

title: For Sale:  Japanese Arisaka Model 99
postcontent:
For sale is a vintage Japanese Arisaka Model 99 and some 7.7x58 ammo.  The rifle operates and shoots decently well;  I have recently shot it.  The serial number is 24481, bolt number 704, and its chrysanthemum is ground off.  From the research I have done on this rifle based on its markings, it is a Toyo Kogyo series 30, which puts its date of manufacturer between mid 1941 and late 1942.  It is most definitely not a "last ditch" model Arisaka;  has the safety on its knurled bolt end and metal butt plate.  It does not have a bipod, the "anti-aircraft wings" on the sight, or the bolt dust cover. 

The wood of the stock is in relatively rough cosmetic shape.  Obviously in its history, a previous owner cut wood off the stock in an attempt to convert its appearance to a more modern rifle stock design, and obviously I know this seriously detracts from this guns value.  The bluing on the metal parts also has wear, but I have seen considerably worse.  The action is very smooth and everything functions perfectly.  I have seen a few near mint Arisaka rifles, but the vast majority of the ones I've seen are in similar condition(other than the chopped stock on this one).

This is a cool rifle, a fun one to shoot.  It was kind of an impulse buy.  Had I done my homework, I would have found that the 7.7x58 ammo is not found much of anywhere(though completely available via online order; I buy it from The Brass King out of MI).  Its relative rarity means ammo is expensive, @$40 per box of 20.  I don't reload so its just not economical for ME to shoot.  I'm including 14 rounds of ammo, $28 worth. I fired the other 6; that brass is also included.  For someone with a stock of 7.7x58 or who reloads, this is not an issue.  It is for me, hence this listing. 

$175 obo. Additional pics available upon request.  Email, call or TEXT! Ben at (513)720-one-five-one-zero

Made in 1981, I bought this gun in 1995 on principle, because Giuliani was mayor of NY city, and it seemed he was going to stamp all over our civil liberties.  I went twice to a shooting range in the Park Ave Armory, which then got closed down because of poor ventilation.   Although I don't know much about guns, I know this pistol is in great condition because my friend who is a gun collector saw it and could not believe it had ever been fired.  He was laughing at me when I told him I didn't know how much was the right amount to clean it, so I just kept cleaning with a soft cloth until it seemed perfect. 

This gun comes with all the original paperwork, box, pamphlets and if you want, you can even have my receipt from 1995 to show provenance (does it work like artwork?)

In the end, NY city won taking away my ability to own a gun by making the license $350, which is too expensive  for me as I am an artist and jewelry designer, and business is not good now.  

So there you have it- a beautiful gun in perfect condition.   

Here is the thing- if I lived in a house instead of a NY city apartment, I would want a gun like this.  The long barrel makes it really easy to shoot straight.  Even not knowing about guns, when I went to the range it was easy to hit the target near the center even though I didn't know how.  Even if I were afraid and my hands were shaking, I think this long barrel would shoot pretty straight. 

Also, because it is so simple to use, there is no worry about the gun getting jammed.    Some bad, violent things have happened to me and if I were alone in a house and someone broke in, this is the gun I would want.  You should get one like this for yourself or your sweetheart.

The new Gen4 has several new features designed to satisfy the most demanding consumers. It is based on a full size G17/G22 MBS (multiple back straps) frame with a reduced short frame trigger mechanism housing. The multiple back strap system allows the user to change the circumference of the grip to fit their individual hand size. The grip has three options; a short frame version, medium frame or large frame that are easily changed and secured with a single pin. The grip angle of the GLOCK "Safe Action" Pistol is not changed by back strap modifications. This ensures that the shooter does not shoot high or low when modifying the back strap or when shooting with a different GLOCK Pistol. The smallest back strap is integrated in the G17 MBS reducing the trigger distance of the standard size G17/G22 frame by 2mm. The medium back strap is a 2mm back strap offering equal size of a standard G17/G22 frame. The large back strap is a 4mm back strap. The magazine release catch of the Gen4 is reversible and enlarged. The reversible magazine catch allows users to switch the catch to the left or right side of the pistol with no additional parts. Additionally, the Gen4 has a new Rough Textured Frame (Gen4 RTF) surface designed to enhance grip traction and is present on the frame as well as the interchangeable back straps. Compact dimensions for open and concealed carry, minimum weight despite large magazine capacity in .40 caliber. This and the reliability of the GLOCK pistol known throughout the world, which was demonstrated through tests and widespread use by US law enforcement agencies, were decisive arguments for the F.B.I. and countless police authorities for introducing the GLOCK 23 as their official service pistol. THE PEARCE FRAME CAVITY INSERT FITS BOTH ADJUSTABLE BACKSTRAPS. I installed a 15 pound hammer spring which lightened the trigger pull a bit while maintaining 100% reliability.  I also have the OEM spring(takes like 2 minutes to swap).
